Claude's full write-up on how to fix it...
========
# RecursiveBinder "dead keys" wedge — diagnosis & recovery
(First seen 2026-07-06, JSON-M4 only. Prereq: `hs` CLI installed via
`require("hs.ipc")` + `hs.ipc.cliInstall` in init.lua.)

## Symptom
- ctrl+space shows the date menu (helper bar appears), BUT the follow-up
  keys (d / b / l / s / t / g) fall through into the focused app instead of
  being caught. No date gets inserted.
- All OTHER Hammerspoon hotkeys (hyper-C/V/L/R, etc.) work normally.
- Reloading config sometimes fixes it, sometimes not.

## Root cause
An OS / WindowServer-level DELIVERY wedge for MODIFIER-LESS hotkeys.
RecursiveBinder's sub-menu keys are bare (no-modifier) hotkeys registered via
Carbon `RegisterEventHotKey`. When wedged, they still REGISTER but macOS won't
DELIVER key events to them, so the keys leak to the app. Hotkeys WITH modifiers
(hyper-*, ctrl+space itself) are unaffected — which is exactly why the trigger
fires but the sub-keys don't catch. Nothing wrong with the config.

## Confirm it (Terminal, via the hs CLI)
1. Rule out innocent causes:
     hs -c "return hs.inspect(hs.eventtap.checkKeyboardModifiers(true))"   # want {_raw = 0}; anything true = stuck modifier (different problem)
     hs -c "return hs.accessibilityState()"                               # want true
2. Prove bare-key delivery is the issue — press ctrl+space, leave the menu up,
   then:
     hs -c "for _,h in ipairs(hs.hotkey.getHotkeys()) do if h.idx=='D' or h.idx=='ESCAPE' then print('modal key registered: '..h.idx) end end"
   If D/ESCAPE ARE listed but pressing 'd' still leaks → registration works,
   delivery is wedged = this bug.
   If D/ESCAPE are listed AT IDLE (no menu open) → the modal is also stuck
   "entered" (orphaned).

## Recovery — try in order, cheapest first
1. Reload config (hyper-R).                     # sometimes enough
2. Jiggle the hotkey table, in the Console:
     x = hs.hotkey.bind({}, "f19", function() end); x:delete()
3. Quit & relaunch Hammerspoon (stronger than reload).
4. Log out and back in (rebuilds the WindowServer login session).
5. Reboot.                                       # guaranteed clear
Note: in the worst instance, steps 1–3 did NOT work and only logout/reboot did.
The state is flaky — escalate as needed.

## DON'T
- Don't use `hs.hotkey.disableAll({}, "d")` / `disableAll({}, "escape")` to clear
  orphaned keys — it disables the live modal's own hotkey objects behind its back
  and corrupts its bookkeeping, forcing a reload anyway. Reload instead.

## Why / permanent fix
RecursiveBinder is built on hs.hotkey.modal → modifier-less Carbon hotkeys, and
has no timeout (an interrupted sequence can strand the modal "entered"). The
deep wedge lives in the WindowServer login session. If it keeps recurring after
a clean reboot, the real fix is to replace the RecursiveBinder modal with an
eventtap-based leader key: keep ctrl+space as the trigger, but capture the
sub-menu keys with hs.eventtap (CGEventTap) — a different OS mechanism that is
immune to the RegisterEventHotKey delivery wedge. (Keeps jasonKeyMap/behavior;
self-contained in recursives.lua; no spoon fork.)

---
A couple of notes on using it: the hs-CLI confirmation steps are the real upgrade over last time — you can now prove which failure mode you're in from the terminal in seconds, instead of poking blindly. And the "try in order" list is deliberately cheapest-first, since a plain reload cleared it today.
========
